Video Description: Wsp√≥≈Çautorami naszych film√≥w jeste≈õcie Wy! https://patronite.pl/globstory ‚û§ Chod≈∫ na FB: https://www.facebook.com/globstory/ ‚û§ Chod≈∫ na Instagrama: ...
Comment: I lived in Tanzania for 8 years. I had to leave 16yrs ago. I am still home sick for Africa, and think of it every day. The people are amazing, friendly, and welcoming. Watching this has been both wonderful, and heart breaking for me. It's wonderful you found such a life. People who live closer to their survival instincts in an uncomplicated life are very lucky. I once said to a close friend there that it was so apparent the average Tanzanian was much happier than the average westerner. He looked at me and asked if I knew why. He's very educated and brilliant in a special way. I asked him why? He smiled and replied, "because we have time for each other. We rely on each other for survival at times. We are never in a hurry" The Maasai for the most part continue to live a simple life. As the country develops, and more money is being made in many sectors, thinks are changing around the cities. They are adopting many western habits and the stresses which come from having more, and wanting more. Materialism is a plague on cultures like this. But once TV arrived and the city folks saw how much of the world lives, the desire for stuff was started.....and is creeping through and polluting a beautiful culture. Many are falling into the trap of thinking having more stuff, will bring more happiness. sigggh. Nakupenda sana dada.

There are trade-offs of course to modern society that you can get anything you want as long as you work hard.  There is no guarantee in modern society either.
In a world with so many bad things, their culture is beautiful. They live so innocently with nature, away from the hustle bustle of city life along with all it's troubles.
You are a wonderful, loving, caring person as well. We need more people like yourself.

Comment: ok and I have so many questions about her birth, I had a very traumatic birth as well and literally died for 19 minutes with no heartbeat. I was revived and ended up having a c-section WITH ABSOLUTELY NO MEDICATION, no general anesthesia, no epidural, I was 100% awake and felt 100 % of it. if I hadn't been in an hospital I would have stayed dead lol so I wonder what the medical facilities are like there, especially for pregnant women. gah I feel so nosy and intrusive but im genuinely curious and want to learn about their culture and village. I feel such a strange kinship with her for some reason, even before I knew she also had a traumatic birth. I had ptsd for years, hell what am I saying, my daughter is 15 and I still have ptsd because of her delivery üòÖ I definitely should have received counseling but didn't and I didn't, and dont, have a support group. it seems her in laws and family are extremely supportive and I wonder if they were kind of like therapist for her. know what I mean ? so I wonder if she suffered from post partum depression and ptsd as I did or if being in an entirely rural setting surrounded by people who love you helped her keep PPD & PTSD at bay? it does take a village to raise a kid and she definitely has that. I live in an extremely rural area in west Texas as well, my closest neighbor is 27 miles away and closest town is 70 miles away. I didn't have anyone or any support so being out here all alone (my husband was in the navy on a submarine and deployed 9 months out of the year so I gave birth to my daughter alone and raised her by myself until she was 4 months) became extremely isolating and exacerbated my ppd and ptsd drastically at the time.

Comment: I find it fascinating how many comments are talking about how humble this lovely soul is or what a 'sacrifice' she's made. I always thought western people envied this way of living; no 9-5 rat-race, no concrete jungle, beautiful nature on your doorstep, no crappy low-quality food in plentitude, less pollution, more freedom of space, etc. If anything I'm always surprised more people don't yearn for lives more similar to this and there hasn't been more emigration or "re-wilding" towards similar ways of life. Most westerners are actually kinda on the breadline; enslaved to low wage and often derogatory jobs, impossibly high rent, spiritual/nature impoverishment and isolation from families/communities whilst being trapped in 50 hour-work weeks. This to me is preferable to that. So I've concluded the people thinking this way of life being an ultimate "sacrifice" are either very wealthy, very lucky or both. Which isn't most of us.
